Introduction
In the previous quest, you learned about Circle Payment API and making card payments with a testcard wallet in a sandbox environment. In this quest, we will be exploring the Circle Payout API by funding a wallet and creating a bank account for sending payouts.
For queries on this quest,  join our Discord, head to the #circle-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.


Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Understand what functionalities Circle Payouts API has
  • Fund your own wallet with test card payment or USDC faucet
  • Create a bank account for sending a payout
  • Send a payout to the created bank account

Deliverable
To successfully complete this quest, you will need to do the following: 
  1. Screenshot of wallet being funded. See Step 8 for more details. 
  2. Screenshot of a successful payout. See Step 8 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Circle Payouts API
The Circle Payouts API allows you to programmatically make fast, global payouts to your customers, vendors, and suppliers. It supports transfers of crypto payments such as USDC, BTC and ETH. Traditional wire transfers are also supported. In this quest, we will be focusing on wire transfers where we will send funds to a bank account.
Step 2: Forking Circle's Core Functionality Collection for Postman
Before sending funds out, we need to ensure that our current test wallet is funded. We will be using the Circle API endpoint to retrieve the balance of funds that are available for use and using Postman to query the wallet balance. If you have not downloaded Postman, refer to Quest 2 Step 6 for instructions on where to download and how to set up Postman.
Head to Circle's Postman Suite where we will be forking the Core Functionality collection. Forking a functionality collection creates a copy of the collection while maintaining a link to the parent. If any changes are made to the parent collection, you can pull the changes to stay up to date with the parent collection.

Under Option 1, next to Core Functionality, click on the ‘Run in Postman’ Button. You will be redirected to another page with the headline 'Fork collection into your workspace'. Click on the ‘Fork Collection’ button.

Next, rename the labels if needed and click on ‘Fork Collection’ again. The Core Functionality API has been successfully forked. 



Close the browser window and return to your Postman application and you should see the API collection there, similar to what you see in 'expected output'. 
Expected output
Step 3: Check Wallet Balance using the Core Functionality API
Now that we have the Circle Core Functionality API collection, go to the ‘Balances’ folder and select ‘List all balances’. 
In the Authorization tab, change the type from 'Inherit auth from parent' to 'Bearer Token'. Next, enter the API key you have generated in Quest 3 into the Token Field.

Click on the blue send button located at the top right of the interface and you should receive a response similar to what you see in 'expected output'. The response displays the amount of available funds and unsettled funds in your circle account. Unsettled funds are funds that are still undergoing processing.
Expected output
Step 4: Obtaining Your Master Wallet Identifier
In this step, we will be funding our own wallet with some funds. There are two ways to fund a wallet. The first way is by using a card to send funds with Circle payment API. For this method, please refer to Quest 4 Step 3 to accept a card payment in the Sandbox environment.
The other way to fund a wallet for testing is to receive USDC from an external blockchain wallet, such as a faucet. In this step, we will fund a wallet using the USDC Testnet Faucet. 

In order to receive funds from an external blockchain wallet, we have to create a deposit address associated with your master wallet. The master wallet identifier is the identifier generated for your master wallet and is used for settling all payments and payouts associated with your master wallet. More details on the master wallet will be provided in the next quest. 

We can obtain your own master wallet identifier by using the Circle Postman API collection. Head to Circle's Postman Suite. Under Option 1, next to API Overview, click on the ‘Run in Postman’ Button. You will be redirected to another page with the headline 'Fork collection into your workspace'. Click on the ‘Fork Collection’ button.

Next, rename the labels if needed and click on ‘Fork Collection’ again. The API Overview API has been successfully forked. 
﻿


Under the Management folder, select 'Get configuration info'. In the Authorization tab, set the type to Bearer Token and ensure your API key is correctly input. 

Click on the 'Send' button. Your master wallet Id should be shown in the response of the API call, similar to what you see in 'expected output'. 
Expected output
Step 5: Funding Your Wallet
Before funding your wallet with the testnet faucet, we will first need to create a blockchain address associated with our master wallet. We will do so using the Circle Accounts API.
Head to Circle's Postman Suite. Under Option 1, next to Accounts API, click on the ‘Run in Postman’ Button. You will be redirected to another page with the headline 'Fork collection into your workspace'. Click on the ‘Fork Collection’ button.

Next, rename the labels if needed and click on ‘Fork Collection’ again. The Accounts API has been successfully forked. 

Under the Wallets folder, select ‘Create a blockchain address’. Under the Params tab, in the Path Variables table, change the value of walletId to your master wallet identifier obtained in the previous step.



After changing the value of your walletId, go to the Authorization tab, change the type to 'Bearer token' and ensure your API key is correctly input.

In the Body tab, you will need to enter a universally unique identifier (UUID) value for ‘IdempotencyKey’. An idempotency key is a key used for handling Idempotent requests where users' API requests can be retransmitted or retried with no additional side effects. For more information about idempotency, refer to Quest 2's Step 4. A UUID is a 36-character alphanumeric string that can be used to identify information, such as a table row in a database.

Generate a UUID from this online generator and change the currency value to ‘USD’ and chain value to ‘ETH’. The final content in the body tab should look like the image shown below. Remember to switch the ‘idempotencyKey’ value to a new one for every request when using the same API endpoint. 



Finally, click the 'Send' button. A successful response should look like the following:



Take down the address from the output above, then proceed to the USDC Testnet Faucet. We will use the USDC Faucet to send USDC to our created blockchain address.

On the USDC Faucet site, click on ETH and input the blockchain address into the field. On submitting, you should see a line of text that says 'USDC will arrive shortly'. 

Next, go to transfers in your sandbox. In the transfers tab, you should see the transaction of funds transferred into your wallet, similar to what you see in 'expected output'. 

Important: Please take a full screenshot of your transaction activity as you will need it for your submission later. More details in the final step. Also, it is fine if your debit amount is different from the 'expected output'.
Expected output
Step 6: Create a Bank Account to Send the Payout to
Now that you have obtained funds in your wallet, we will create a bank account in order to send some funds as payouts. To do that, we will need to use the Circle Payouts API.
Head to Circle's Postman Suite. Under Option 1, next to Payouts API, click on the ‘Run in Postman’ Button. You will be redirected to another page with the headline "Fork collection into your workspace". Click on the ‘Fork Collection’ button.

Next, rename the labels if needed and click on ‘Fork Collection’ again. The Payouts API has been successfully forked. 

Under the Wires folder, select 'Create a Wire bank account'. In the Authorization tab, set the type to Bearer Token and ensure your API key is correctly input. 

Next, navigate to the Body tab. It contains predefined fields of details of a Bank account. The only change you need to make is the ‘idempotencyKey’, which you will need to fill with a new UUID. Your body should look similar to the following:



Click 'Send'. A successful response should look like this, where the status is pending. 



Wait for a few minutes and the status will change from ‘pending’ to 'complete’. Alternatively, you can click on send again, using the same idempotency key, and the status will be updated, as shown in 'expected output'.

Do take note of the ‘id’ value. This is the bank account identifier and we will need that value in the next step.
Expected output
Step 7: Send a Payout to a Bank Account
Since we have funded our wallet and created a Wire bank account to deposit funds to, we can start creating a payout. We will be using the Payouts API Postman collection to do this. Under Payouts, select ‘Create a payout’.
In the Authorization tab, set the type to Bearer Token and ensure your API key is correctly input. In the ‘Body’ tab, you will find that there are pre-filled fields. We will need to change some of these values. Firstly, generate a new UUID for the idempotencyKey value. Change the destination id to the bank account identifier you obtained in the previous step. For the source id, change it to the master wallet identifier you obtained in Step 4. For the amount, you can enter an amount of your choice. Finally, click the 'Send' button.



A successful response should look like the image below, with the status indicated as 'pending'.



You need to wait for a few minutes before the payout transaction is changed from ‘pending’ to ‘complete’. 
Click on the 'Send' button again with the same idempotency key in the create payout API endpoint. You should then see a response similar to 'expected output', where the status is set to complete and a transaction fee of 25 USD is deducted from the overall balance.

Important: Take a full screenshot of your Postman interface at this point. You will need it for your submission later. ﻿
Expected output
Step 8: Let’s Ace Your Submissions! Preparing Your Submission!
You have reached the end! Now to ensure you successfully complete this quest! There are 2 screenshots that are required for this quest.
In Step 5, you had to take a screenshot of your entire screen showing your transfer details. 

Your screenshot should show:
  • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
  • The transfer details showing the source, destination and transfer ID.
  • All parts in red boxes in Step 5's ‘Expected output’ are visible in your screenshot(s)!

When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided: C58_Q5_yourstackupname_1.png.

In Step 7, you had to take a screenshot of your entire screen showing a completed payout transaction. 

Your screenshot should show:
  • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
  • The entire API response, including a 'complete' status, destination id and walletId.
  • All parts in red boxes in Step 7's ‘Expected output’ are visible in your screenshot(s)!

When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided: C58_Q5_yourstackupname_2.png.

Attach these two screenshots to your submission and you are good to go!
